chnologies humans create simultaneously shape humans themselves. By means of case studies of technologies as diverse as video cameras, electric cars, pregnancy tests, and genetic screenings, this volume considers the implications of this "co-production" of technology and society for our philosophical and political ideas. Are only humans endowed with social, political, and moral agency, or does our technology share those qualities? And if so, how should we understand-or practice-a politics of technology?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgent (Philosophy). 0aTechnologyxPolitical aspects. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBrey, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouns, Margo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDisco, Cornelis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElzen, Boelie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbers, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbers, Hans, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJelsma, Jaap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKockelkoren, Petran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelis, Annemiek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOudshoorn, Nelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPopkema, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStemerding, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwierstra, Tsjalling, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerbeek, Peter-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ava